<topic xml:id="ha-maintenance-taking-cluster-out-of-maintenance-mode"
 role="task" xml:lang="en"
 xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.2"
 xmlns:its="http://www.w3.org/2005/11/its"
 xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
 xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
 xmlns:trans="http://docbook.org/ns/transclusion">
  <info>
    <title>Taking the cluster out of maintenance mode</title>
    <meta name="maintainer" content="tahlia.richardson@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract>
      <para>
        Taking the cluster out of maintenance mode puts the resources back under cluster management
        and protection.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>

  <variablelist role="tabs">
    <varlistentry>
      <term>&crmshell;</term>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          You can perform this procedure on any node in the cluster.
        </para>
        <procedure>
          <step>
            <para>
              Log in either as the &rootuser; user or as a user with <command>sudo</command>
              privileges.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Check the status of the cluster:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.user;<command>sudo crm status</command></screen>
            <para>
              If the nodes have the status <literal>UNCLEAN (Offline)</literal>, wait until they
              change to <literal>Online</literal>.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              If the nodes are <literal>Online</literal>, put the cluster back into normal
              operation:
            </para>
<screen>&prompt.user;<command>sudo crm maintenance off</command></screen>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Check the status of the cluster again. The resources should no longer show the
              status <literal>(maintenance)</literal>.
            </para>
          </step>
        </procedure>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>&hawk;</term>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          You can use &hawk; on any machine with a Web browser and network access to the nodes.
        </para>
        <procedure>
          <step>
            <para>
              In a Web browser, go to
              <literal>https://<replaceable>HAWKSERVER</replaceable>:7630/</literal> and log in.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              In the left navigation bar, select <menuchoice><guimenu>Configuration</guimenu>
              <guimenu>Cluster Configuration</guimenu></menuchoice>.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              From the <literal>maintenance-mode</literal> drop-down list, select
              <guimenu>No</guimenu>.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              Click <guimenu>Apply</guimenu>.
            </para>
            <para>
              A message at the top of the screen shows if the action was successful.
            </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
              In the left navigation bar, select <menuchoice><guimenu>Monitoring</guimenu>
              <guimenu>Status</guimenu></menuchoice>.
            </para>
            <para>
              The resources should have green or red <guimenu>Status</guimenu> icons instead of
              wrench icons.
            </para>
          </step>
        </procedure>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
</topic>
